# tiktok-motion-transfer

<note id="overview" label="Overview">
## TikTok Motion Transfer Pipeline

This notebook downloads a TikTok video and uses **Kling Motion Control** (fal.ai) to transfer the motion onto a character from a reference image.

### Flow
1. **Check Environment** — Verify `FAL_KEY`, `uv`, and `ffmpeg` are available
2. **Install Skills** — Add tiktok-downloader and keling-motion skills
3. **Video Input** — Enter the TikTok video URL to download
4. **Download Video** — Download the TikTok video as the motion reference
5. **Reference Image** — Provide a reference image of the character to animate
6. **Review Inputs** — Verify the downloaded video and reference image before generation
7. **Configure & Generate** — Set motion control options and generate the video
8. **Done** — Final output summary
</note>

<shell id="check-env" label="Check Environment">
#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Checking Environment ==="

if [ -z "$FAL_KEY" ]; then
  echo "ERROR: FAL_KEY is not set."
  echo ""
  echo "Get an API key at: https://fal.ai/dashboard/keys"
  echo "Then set it:"
  echo '  export FAL_KEY="your-key-here"'
  echo "Or add it to your .env file."
  exit 1
fi

echo "FAL_KEY is set."
echo ""
echo "=== Checking uv ==="
if command -v uv &> /dev/null; then
  echo "uv $(uv --version) found"
else
  echo "ERROR: uv is not installed. Install from https://docs.astral.sh/uv/"
  exit 1
fi

echo ""
echo "=== Checking ffmpeg ==="
if command -v ffmpeg &> /dev/null; then
  echo "ffmpeg found: $(ffmpeg -version 2>&1 | head -1)"
else
  echo "WARNING: ffmpeg is not installed. Some features may not work."
  echo "Install with: brew install ffmpeg"
fi

echo ""
echo "=== Environment OK ==="
</shell>

<shell id="install-skills" label="Install Skills">
#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Installing TikTok Downloader Skill ==="
npx @anytio/pspm@latest add @user/anyt/tiktok-downloader -y

echo ""
echo "=== Installing Keling Motion Skill ==="
npx @anytio/pspm@latest add @user/anyt/keling-motion -y

echo ""
echo "=== Verify Installed Skills ==="
ls -la .pspm/skills/ 2>/dev/null || echo "Skills directory not found"

echo ""
echo "=== Setup Output Directories ==="
mkdir -p video reference output
echo "Created: video/ reference/ output/"
</shell>

<input id="video-input" label="TikTok Video URL">
## Which TikTok video do you want to use?

Enter the TikTok video URL that contains the motion/dance/action you want to transfer onto your character.

<form type="json">
{
  "fields": [
    {
      "name": "videoUrl",
      "type": "text",
      "label": "TikTok Video URL",
      "required": true,
      "default": "https://www.tiktok.com/@bismarckclass_/video/7606927884959206669?is_from_webapp=1",
      "placeholder": "https://www.tiktok.com/@user/video/..."
    }
  ]
}
</form>
</input>

<task id="download-video" label="Download TikTok Video">
Using the **tiktok-downloader** skill, download the TikTok video from the URL provided in `video-input`.

- Download the video in MP4 format
- Save to the `video/` directory
- After downloading, list the files in `video/` so we know the exact filename

**Output:** video/*.mp4
</task>

<input id="reference-image" label="Reference Image">
## Provide a Reference Image

The reference image defines the character's appearance. The motion from the TikTok video will be transferred onto this character.

Provide a path to a local image file or a URL. Supported formats: PNG, JPEG, WebP, GIF (max 10MB).

<form type="json">
{
  "fields": [
    {
      "name": "imagePath",
      "type": "text",
      "label": "Reference Image (path or URL)",
      "required": true,
      "default": "bear.jpg",
      "placeholder": "/path/to/character.png or https://example.com/character.png"
    },
    {
      "name": "imageDescription",
      "type": "textarea",
      "label": "Character Description (optional)",
      "required": false,
      "default": "A cute brown teddy bear with heart patches, presenting a golden trophy",
      "rows": 2,
      "placeholder": "Describe the character or scene, e.g., 'A cartoon robot dancing in a city'"
    }
  ]
}
</form>
</input>

<task id="prepare-image" label="Prepare Reference Image">
Copy the reference image from `reference-image` into the `reference/` directory.

- If a local file path was provided, copy it to `reference/character.png` (or keep original extension)
- If a URL was provided, download it to `reference/character.png`
- Verify the image exists and show its file size

**Output:** reference/character.png (or matching extension)
</task>

<break id="review-inputs" label="Review Inputs">
Review the downloaded TikTok video and reference image before generating the motion-controlled video.

Files to check:
- `video/` — The downloaded TikTok video (motion reference)
- `reference/` — The character reference image

Continue when you're satisfied with both inputs.
</break>

<input id="motion-config" label="Motion Control Settings">
## Configure Motion Control

Choose how the motion transfer should work.

<form type="json">
{
  "fields": [
    {
      "name": "orientation",
      "type": "select",
      "label": "Character Orientation",
      "required": true,
      "default": "video",
      "options": [
        { "value": "image", "label": "Match reference image (max 10s output)" },
        { "value": "video", "label": "Match reference video (max 30s output)" }
      ],
      "description": "Controls whether the generated character's orientation matches the image or video"
    },
    {
      "name": "keepSound",
      "type": "checkbox",
      "label": "Keep Original Sound",
      "default": true,
      "description": "Keep the audio from the reference TikTok video"
    },
    {
      "name": "prompt",
      "type": "textarea",
      "label": "Descriptive Prompt (optional)",
      "required": false,
      "default": "A cute teddy bear presenting a golden trophy, standing outdoors",
      "rows": 2,
      "placeholder": "Optional: describe the scene, e.g., 'A character dancing energetically in a ballroom'"
    }
  ]
}
</form>
</input>

<task id="generate-motion-video" label="Generate Motion-Controlled Video">
Using the **keling-motion** skill, generate a motion-controlled video combining the reference image and TikTok video.

- Use the reference image from `reference/` (the file prepared in the `prepare-image` step)
- Use the downloaded TikTok video from `video/` as the motion reference
- Apply the settings from `motion-config`:
  - Character orientation setting
  - Keep sound setting
  - Descriptive prompt (if provided)
- Save the output to `output/` with filename `motion_result.mp4`

**Output:** output/motion_result.mp4
</task>

<note id="complete" label="Pipeline Complete">
## Motion Transfer Complete

### Generated Files
```
video/                    # Downloaded TikTok video (motion reference)
reference/                # Character reference image
output/motion_result.mp4  # Final motion-controlled video
```

### What Was Used
- **TikTok Downloader** — Downloaded the reference motion video
- **Kling Motion Control** (fal.ai) — Transferred motion onto the character image

### Next Steps
- Try different reference images with the same motion video
- Try different TikTok videos with the same character image
- Adjust character orientation (`image` vs `video`) for different effects
- Add or remove the descriptive prompt for different results
</note>

